        "children": [
          {
            "id": "cat_impl_details",
            "label": "Impl. Details",
            "type": "label",
            "count": 20,
            "children": [
              {
                "id": "rule_10",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "All collectors must follow a consistent constructor pattern:\n```go\nfunc NewXCollector(logger logr.Logger, config performance.CollectionConfig) (*XCollector, error) {\n    // 1. Validate paths are absolute\n    if !filepath.IsAbs(config.HostProcPath) {\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"HostProcPath must be an absolute path, got: %q\", config.HostProcPath)\n    }\n    if !filepath.IsAbs(config.HostSysPath) {  // If collector uses sysfs\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"HostSysPath must be an absolute path, got: %q\", config.HostSysPath)\n    }\n    \n    // 2. Define capabilities\n    capabilities := performance.CollectorCapabilities{\n        SupportsOneShot:    true,\n        SupportsContinuous: false,\n        RequiresRoot:       false,\n        RequiresEBPF:       false,\n        MinKernelVersion:   \"2.6.0\",\n    }\n    \n    // 3. Return collector with pre-computed paths\n    return &XCollector{\n        BaseCollector: performance.NewBaseCollector(...),\n        specificPath: filepath.Join(config.HostProcPath, \"specific/file\"),\n    }, nil\n}\n```",
                  "originalHeader": "Constructor Pattern"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 147,
                  "line_end": 174
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_11",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "Every collector must include a compile-time interface check:\n```go\n// Compile-time interface check\nvar _ performance.Collector = (*NetworkCollector)(nil)\n```",
                  "originalHeader": "Compile-Time Interface Checks"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 177,
                  "line_end": 181
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_12",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "Collectors must clearly distinguish between critical and optional data and should never panic:\n\n- **Critical files**: Return error immediately if unavailable (e.g., /proc/loadavg for LoadCollector)\n- **Optional files**: Log warning and continue with graceful degradation (e.g., /sys/class/net/* metadata)\n- **Parse errors**: Handle based on field importance - critical fields cause errors, optional fields are logged\n- **Panic prevention**: Collectors must use proper error handling instead of panicking. All errors should be returned to the caller",
                  "originalHeader": "Error Handling Strategy"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 205,
                  "line_end": 211
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_13",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "When optional data is unavailable, collectors should:\n1. Log the issue at appropriate verbosity level (V(2) for debug info)\n2. Continue processing with available data\n3. Return partial results rather than failing entirely\n4. Document which fields may be missing in degraded mode",
                  "originalHeader": "Error Handling Strategy"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 213,
                  "line_end": 218
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_14",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "In order to use a collector, it has to be added to the registry so that the manager knows about it.\nThis is typically done in the init() function in the source file where the collector is implemented:",
                  "originalHeader": "Adding Collector to Registry"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 232,
                  "line_end": 233
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_15",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "Use `PartialNewContinuousPointCollector` if the collector is collecting runtime statistics.",
                  "originalHeader": "Adding Collector to Registry"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 237,
                  "line_end": 237
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_16",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "Use `PartialOnceContinuousCollector` when collecting hardware information or if the collector needs to run just once.",
                  "originalHeader": "Adding Collector to Registry"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 248,
                  "line_end": 248
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_17",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "- Don't test static properties (Name, RequiresRoot)\n- Don't test compile-time interface checks (e.g., `var _ performance.Collector = (*XCollector)(nil)`)\n- Focus on parsing logic and error handling\n- Use realistic test data from actual /proc files\n- Test collectors in `collectors_test` package (external testing)\n- Name test functions consistently: `TestXCollector_Constructor`, `TestXCollector_Collect`\n- Use descriptive test names that explain the scenario\n- Group related test scenarios in the same test function",
                  "originalHeader": "Testing Principles"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "ListItem",
                  "line_start": 320,
                  "line_end": 327
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_18",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "- **Type-level documentation**: Explain purpose, data sources, references\n- **Method documentation**: Include format examples and error handling strategy\n- **Inline documentation**: Explain complex parsing logic or non-obvious decisions\n- **Reference links**: Include kernel documentation links where applicable",
                  "originalHeader": "Documentation Standards"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "ListItem",
                  "line_start": 331,
                  "line_end": 334
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_19",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "When adding a new performance collector:\n\n1. **Define the data structure** in `pkg/performance/types.go`\n2. **Create the collector** in `pkg/performance/collectors/your_collector.go`\n   - Include compile-time interface check\n   - Follow constructor pattern with path validation\n   - Document error handling strategy\n3. **Create comprehensive tests** in `pkg/performance/collectors/your_collector_test.go`\n   - Use `collectors_test` package\n   - Include constructor tests\n   - Add helper functions following naming patterns\n   - Test edge cases and error scenarios\n4. **Update collector registry**\n   - Write an init() function in `your_collector.go` to add the collector to the registry",
                  "originalHeader": "Collector Development Workflow"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 338,
                  "line_end": 352
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_20",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "**Early returns** to reduce nesting",
                  "originalHeader": "Code Style"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "SHOULD",
                  "format": "ListItem",
                  "line_start": 443,
                  "line_end": 443
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_21",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "**Functional patterns** where applicable",
                  "originalHeader": "Code Style"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "SHOULD",
                  "format": "ListItem",
                  "line_start": 444,
                  "line_end": 444
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_22",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "**Concise implementations** without unnecessary comments",
                  "originalHeader": "Code Style"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "SHOULD",
                  "format": "ListItem",
                  "line_start": 445,
                  "line_end": 445
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_23",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "**Error wrapping** with context",
                  "originalHeader": "Code Style"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "ListItem",
                  "line_start": 446,
                  "line_end": 446
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_24",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "Always use CO-RE Macros\n   - Prefer `BPF_CORE_READ()` over direct field access\n   - Use `BPF_CORE_READ_STR()` for string fields\n   - Check field existence with `BPF_CORE_FIELD_EXISTS()`",
                  "originalHeader": "CO-RE Best Practices"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "ListItem",
                  "line_start": 554,
                  "line_end": 558
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_25",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "Handle Missing Fields Gracefully\n   - Not all kernel versions have all fields\n   - Use conditional compilation or runtime checks\n   - Provide fallback behavior",
                  "originalHeader": "CO-RE Best Practices"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "ListItem",
                  "line_start": 564,
                  "line_end": 567
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_26",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "For new `.bpf.c` files:\n1. Create `ebpf/src/your_program.bpf.c`\n2. Include CO-RE headers:\n   ```c\n   #include \"vmlinux.h\"\n   #include <bpf/bpf_core_read.h>\n   ```\n3. Use CO-RE macros for kernel struct access\n4. Add to `BPF_PROGS` in `ebpf/Makefile`\n5. Run `make build-ebpf`",
                  "originalHeader": "Adding New eBPF Programs"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 519,
                  "line_end": 529
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_27",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "For new struct definitions:\n1. Create `ebpf/include/your_collector_types.h` with C structs\n2. Run `make generate-ebpf-types` to generate Go types\n3. Generated files appear in `pkg/performance/collectors/`",
                  "originalHeader": "Adding New eBPF Programs"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 531,
                  "line_end": 534
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_28",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "When implementing collectors that support continuous collection (ContinuousCollector interface), follow this standardized pattern for proper lifecycle management",
                  "originalHeader": "Continuous Collector Pattern"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 393,
                  "line_end": 393
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_29",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "Document the error handling strategy in method comments:\n```go\n// collectNetworkStats reads network statistics\n//\n// Error handling strategy:\n// - /proc/net/dev is critical - returns error if unavailable\n// - /sys/class/net/* files are optional - logs warnings but continues\n// - Malformed lines in /proc/net/dev are skipped with logging\n// - Never panics - all errors are returned to caller\n```",
                  "originalHeader": "Error Handling Strategy"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "Paragraph",
                  "line_start": 220,
                  "line_end": 230
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "rule_30",
                "type": "rule",
                "content": {
                  "text": "Test Across Kernels\n   - Test on minimum supported kernel (4.18)\n   - Verify on latest stable kernel\n   - Use KIND clusters with different kernel versions",
                  "originalHeader": "CO-RE Best Practices"
                },
                "metadata": {
                  "strength": "MUST",
                  "format": "ListItem",
                  "line_start": 560,
                  "line_end": 563
                }
              }
            ]
